<DocsLayout title="Architecture" description="Design the architecture for Harbour Health — video platform selection, data isolation, prescription workflow, infrastructure, and security.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Architecture</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You design this entirely. Nine projects of architecture decisions have prepared you for this. The guidance here is minimal — the decisions are yours.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Generate the architecture document from your PRD and design spec. The key decisions below are the ones that require the most thought. Each should result in an ADR (Architecture Decision Record) explaining what you chose and why.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Key decisions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">1. Video platform</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Aisha said: "reliable and works on bad internet." You must research the options, evaluate them against this requirement, and choose. Write an ADR justifying your decision.</p>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto my-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
              <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Platform</th>
              <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Free tier</th>
              <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">WebRTC</th>
              <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Low bandwidth</th>
              <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Recording</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold">Daily.co</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">10,000 min/mo</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Good adaptive quality</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes (paid)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold">Twilio Video</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Pay-per-minute</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Granular control</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold">Zoom SDK</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Limited</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Proprietary</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Good (Zoom's network)</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Key evaluation criteria:</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
        <li><strong class="text-text">Low-bandwidth performance:</strong> Does the platform adapt video quality to the connection? WebRTC-based platforms generally handle this well.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Browser-based:</strong> No app download. Patients join from a link in the browser.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">API integration:</strong> Can you programmatically create rooms and generate join links?</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Free tier:</strong> Enough for development and initial launch with 50 patients?</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Documentation quality:</strong> You'll be verifying AI-generated integration code against the docs (same skill as P4's Stripe verification).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">2. Data isolation</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Patient data must be scoped to the patient and their specialist. No one else — not other patients, not other specialists, not even admins unless explicitly required for the prescription workflow.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">This must be enforced at the database level, not just the application level:</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
        <li>Every query for patient data includes a <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">WHERE</code> clause scoping to the authenticated user</li>
        <li>Consultation records join patient_id and specialist_id — both must match the requesting user</li>
        <li>PostgreSQL row-level security (RLS) as an additional layer, or application-level enforcement with comprehensive testing</li>
        <li>The admin role can view prescription requests (for the review queue) but not full consultation notes</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">3. Prescription workflow</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Specialist writes a prescription request. It enters a queue. Admin reviews it. Notification goes to the patient's local GP (email). This is async — not real-time.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Architecture decisions:</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
        <li>Prescription request model: specialist_id, patient_id, consultation_id, medication details, GP contact info, status (pending/reviewed/sent)</li>
        <li>Status transitions: pending → reviewed (admin) → sent (email to GP) or rejected (admin with reason)</li>
        <li>Email delivery: SES or similar for sending to GP. Delivery confirmation logged.</li>
        <li>Audit trail: every status change logged with timestamp and who made the change</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">4. Infrastructure</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">The full AWS stack from P9, adapted for Harbour Health's requirements. Terraform modules reused where possible, new modules where needed.</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
        <li>EC2 Auto Scaling Group behind an Application Load Balancer (start small, scale with demand)</li>
        <li>RDS PostgreSQL with Multi-AZ for reliability (medical data — downtime during a consultation is unacceptable)</li>
        <li>CloudFront for static assets and low-latency delivery to regional users</li>
        <li>S3 for static assets and potentially consultation recordings (if required)</li>
        <li>Terraform modules: networking, compute, database, monitoring — adapted from P9</li>
        <li>AWS Secrets Manager for all secrets (JWT key, database credentials, video API key, email credentials)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">5. Security</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Everything you built in P5, plus healthcare-specific concerns:</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
        <li>JWT authentication (from P5) with short token expiry for health data</li>
        <li>RDS encryption at rest enabled</li>
        <li>HTTPS everywhere — no exceptions</li>
        <li>Audit logging: every access to patient data logged (who, when, what record, what action). Separate audit log table, append-only.</li>
        <li>CORS restricted to the frontend domain</li>
        <li>CSP headers configured to prevent XSS</li>
        <li>Rate limiting on auth endpoints</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>ADRs are not optional.</strong> For each of the five decisions above, write an Architecture Decision Record: context, options considered, decision, and consequences. These become part of the handover documentation. When someone asks "why Daily.co and not Zoom?" the ADR answers the question.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is the PRD and design spec for Harbour Health, a telehealth consultation platform:

[Paste your PRD here]
[Paste your design spec here]

Using the following architecture template, create a complete technical architecture document.

Tech stack: React frontend, FastAPI backend, RDS PostgreSQL (multi-AZ), EC2 ASG behind ALB, CloudFront, S3, Terraform with modules, Prometheus + Grafana, Sentry, PagerDuty, Alembic for migrations.

Key architecture decisions to address (each as an ADR):
1. Video platform selection — evaluate Daily.co, Twilio Video, Zoom SDK against requirements (low bandwidth, browser-based, API integration, free tier)
2. Data isolation — database-level enforcement of patient-specialist scoping
3. Prescription workflow — async pipeline with status tracking and audit trail
4. Infrastructure — full AWS stack with Terraform modules
5. Security — JWT auth, encryption at rest/in transit, audit logging, CORS, CSP

Additional requirements:
- WCAG 2.1 AA accessibility considerations in component architecture
- Failure handling: specialist no-show, video service outage, patient connection drop
- Audit logging architecture: separate append-only table, what gets logged, retention

[Paste architecture template here]`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Review guidance</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">By now you know what a good architecture document looks like. The new checks:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Video platform ADR:</strong> Does it evaluate multiple options against the "bad internet" requirement? Is the choice justified?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Data isolation is database-level?</strong> Not just "the API checks permissions" — the queries themselves are scoped. Patient A's data is unreachable from Patient B's queries.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Audit logging is specified?</strong> What gets logged, where it's stored, how long it's kept. Not "we'll add logging" — the schema for the audit table.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Failure cases are handled?</strong> What happens when the video service is down? When the specialist is late? When the patient's internet drops mid-consultation?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Infrastructure matches the scale?</strong> 50-500 users. ASG makes sense. Kubernetes does not. Multi-AZ for the database makes sense (medical data). Multi-region does not (yet).</li>
  </ul>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: video APIs</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">You need to choose one. Here's what exists and what matters for telehealth.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Daily.co</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">WebRTC-based. Good adaptive quality for low bandwidth. Simple API — create a room, get a join link. Free tier: 10,000 participant minutes/month. Good documentation. Recommended starting point for this project.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Twilio Video</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Mature platform. WebRTC. Granular control over video quality, network topology, and recording. Pay-per-minute pricing. More complex API but more flexibility. Good for production at scale.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Zoom SDK</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Embedded Zoom experience. Users familiar with the interface. Requires Zoom account. SDK integration is more complex than API-first platforms. Free tier limited.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Vonage (formerly TokBox)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">WebRTC. Similar to Twilio Video. Strong in healthcare and telehealth. Good adaptive bitrate. Pay-per-minute.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Amazon Chime SDK</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">AWS-native video. Good if you're already deep in AWS. Pay-per-minute. Integration with other AWS services is seamless but adds vendor lock-in.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Agora</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Real-time engagement platform. Low latency. Strong in Asia-Pacific. Free tier: 10,000 minutes/month. More gaming/social focused but works for telehealth.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">For Harbour Health: Daily.co is the recommended starting point. WebRTC adapts to bandwidth (critical for regional Australia), the API is simple, the free tier covers initial launch, and the documentation is good for verifying AI-generated code. But the choice is yours — justify it in the ADR.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: compliance frameworks</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Healthcare data is regulated everywhere. Harbour Health operates under Australian law, but the technical controls overlap with international standards.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Australian Privacy Act 1988</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What applies to Harbour Health. Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) govern collection, use, and disclosure of personal information. Health data is "sensitive information" with additional protections.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">HIPAA (US)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">The US standard for health data. Encryption, access controls, audit trails, breach notification. Doesn't apply to Harbour Health, but the technical controls are nearly identical.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">SOC 2</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">An audit framework covering security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, and privacy. Not a law — a certification that proves your controls work. Common requirement for B2B SaaS.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">ISO 27001</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">International standard for information security management. Comprehensive framework covering risk assessment, access control, cryptography, and incident management. Often required for enterprise healthcare contracts.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">The common thread: encryption (at rest and in transit), access controls, audit logging, and data retention policies. Build these well and you satisfy the technical requirements of most compliance frameworks.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: audit logging</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Audit logging answers the question: who accessed what data, when? For healthcare, this is a compliance requirement. Here are the approaches.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Application-level logging</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. The application writes to an audit_log table on every data access. You control exactly what gets logged. Requires discipline — every endpoint must include the logging call.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Database triggers</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">PostgreSQL triggers that fire on INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE. Catches all changes, even those made outside the application (e.g., direct database access). More comprehensive but harder to include application context (who made the request).</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">AWS CloudTrail</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Logs all AWS API calls. Covers infrastructure changes (who modified the security group?) but not application-level data access. Complementary to application-level logging, not a replacement.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">ELK Stack (Elasticsearch + Logstash + Kibana)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Centralised log management. Application logs, access logs, and audit logs all searchable in one place. Kibana dashboards for visualisation. Heavy to run but powerful at scale.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">For Harbour Health: application-level logging to a dedicated audit_log table, supplemented by CloudTrail for infrastructure changes. The audit_log table is append-only — no updates, no deletes. This is the table that answers "who saw this patient's data?" during a compliance review.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: healthcare tech</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Healthcare technology has its own standards and terminology. You don't need to implement these, but knowing they exist helps you ask the right questions and understand the domain.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">HL7 FHIR</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources. The modern standard for exchanging healthcare data between systems. RESTful APIs, JSON format. If Harbour Health ever integrates with hospital systems or Medicare, FHIR is the standard.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Electronic Health Records (EHR)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Systems like Epic, Cerner, and Medical Director that store patient medical history. Harbour Health is NOT an EHR — it stores consultation notes, not full medical records. Important distinction.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Telehealth regulations (AU)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">In Australia, telehealth consultations have been covered under Medicare since 2020 (made permanent after COVID). The Australian Health Practitioner Regulation Agency (AHPRA) regulates practitioners. The platform facilitates consultations — it doesn't replace medical regulation.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Digital health identifiers</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">In Australia, Healthcare Provider Identifiers (HPI) identify practitioners. Individual Healthcare Identifiers (IHI) identify patients. Harbour Health doesn't integrate with these yet, but they're part of the ecosystem.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">Harbour Health is a telehealth platform, not an EHR system. The scope is consultations, notes, and prescription requests. Knowing the broader healthcare tech ecosystem helps you understand what Harbour Health is — and importantly, what it is not.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: implementation</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Architecture reviewed. Time to create the backlog and start building.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/10/implementation"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Implementation →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
